 Change in Octavia Butler’s Speculative Fiction -- tAliens Without and Within: Abjection from Tetter to Tumor in Toni Morrison’s Novels -- tAfrican American Women and Stigma: Reactions to Medical Targeting for HIV and COVID-19 -- tDisplacement: Constructing and Countering Collapse -- tSpilling Over: Morality and Epidemiology in Ancient and Contemporary Contexts -- tSocrates in the City of Bones: Plato’s Republic and August Wilson’s Gem of the Ocean -- tDisplacement and Discipline: Refugees and the Unemployed in Living and Public Spaces in Greece -- tResettled Refugees in the American South: Discourses of Victimization and Transgression in Clarkston, Georgia -- tMaking the Beams of Architectural Poetry out of the Rubble of Displacement: Czesław Miłosz, Taha Muhammad Ali, and the Lyric of Constructed World Citizenry -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiscrimination, stigmatization, xenophobia, heightened securitization – fear and blaming of "aliens within" – characterize the world infected by COVID-19. Such fears have a long cultural history, however, particularly in connecting pathology with race, poverty, and migration. This volume explores theory and narratives of disease, danger, and displacement through the lenses of cultural, literary, and film studies, historical representation, ethnics studies, sociology and cultural geography, classics, music, and linguistics. Investigations range from, for example, illness discourse in the ancient classics to images of perilous intruders in the Age of Trump, from the Haitian Revolution and subsequent zombie stereotypes to current, problematic refugee resettlement in the US South and Greek islands, from the urban underworld in nineteenth-century sensation novels to ethnic women "on the stroll" in coronavirus times. The collection is organized into three thematically intertwined parts: Stigmatizing the Racialized Underclass; Pathologizing the Other; Constructing and Countering Collapse. It examines changing or recurrent aporias in tropes of belonging and exclusion, as well as the birthing of new forms of identity, agency, and countercultural expression.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aArts and the poor. 0aMarginality, Social. 0aPeople with social disabilities. 0aPoor. 0aRacexSocial aspects. 0aSocial representations. 0aStigmatization.  adisaster capitalism.  aothering.  apathology and race.  aunderclass.1 aAdamik, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllende Goitía, Noel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisgone, Regina E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Hunter H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKampragkos, Chrysovalantis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurjatto-Renard, Patrycja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaforcade, Geoffroy de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaforcade, Geoffroy de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLaws, Page R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee Robinson, Briana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartanovschi, Ludmila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetzger, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihăilescu, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRonee Washington, Adrienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRozga, Michele E., econtributor.4ctb4https: